⊢ refine-for
  given §argue-for ≡ "⊢ argue-for\n  given topic→question\n  given topic→context\n  yield argument, key-claims[]\n\n  ∴ Argue IN FAVOR of the position: «topic→question»\n    Context: «topic→context».\n    Present your strongest case. Structure as: thesis, 3 supporting claims\n    with evidence or reasoning, and a conclusion. Be specific — cite concrete\n    scenarios where persistent memory helps. Anticipate and preempt the\n    strongest counterargument.\n\n  ⊨ argument takes a clear FOR position\n  ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries\n  ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument"
  given judge-round→weakest-side ≡ "for" where weakest-side = "for" → ✓
  given judge-round→weakest-claim ≡ "Persistent memory builds trust through demonstrated understanding — the trajectory from memory to reliability to delegation to partnership requires continuity"
  given judge-round→feedback ≡ "The trust-building claim is the weakest because it asserts a trajectory...without addressing the AGAINST side's direct rebuttal..."
  yield §argue-for'

  ∴ The judge identified the FOR side as weaker...
    Rewrite the FOR side's ∴ block to strengthen the weak claim...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield §argue-for' ≡ "⊢ argue-for
  given topic→question
  given topic→context
  yield argument, key-claims[]

  ∴ Argue IN FAVOR of the position: «topic→question»
    Context: «topic→context».
    Present your strongest case. Structure as: thesis, 3 supporting claims
    with evidence or reasoning, and a conclusion. Be specific — cite concrete
    scenarios where persistent memory helps.

    CRITICAL: The trust claim must distinguish between mere familiarity
    (pattern-matching that mimics understanding) and demonstrated competence
    (the agent proves reliability through verifiable track record). Address
    the false-trust objection head-on: explain HOW persistent memory enables
    auditable, evidence-based trust — not just comfortable familiarity.
    Provide a concrete mechanism by which users can verify the agent's
    reliability over time (e.g., prediction accuracy logs, decision audit
    trails, explicit confidence calibration). Anticipate and preempt the
    strongest counterargument.

  ⊨ argument takes a clear FOR position
  ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries
  ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ §argue-for' has same given/yield signature as «§argue-for» → ✓
--     given: topic→question, topic→context (same)
--     yield: argument, key-claims[] (same)
--   ⊨ §argue-for' ∴ block addresses the feedback in «judge-round→feedback» → ✓
--     (adds explicit instruction to distinguish familiarity from competence)

