-- LLM evaluation:

  yield argument ≡ "Persistent memory is essential for AI agents to fulfill their core purpose: being genuinely useful to humans over time.

THESIS: AI agents should have persistent memory because it transforms them from stateless tools into adaptive partners with verifiable track records, directly improving capability, trust, and alignment.

CLAIM 1: Persistent memory enables compounding capability. A software engineer's AI assistant that remembers their codebase architecture, preferred frameworks, and past debugging sessions becomes exponentially more useful. Without memory, the engineer re-explains their tech stack every session. Concrete scenario: a medical researcher using an AI to survey literature across months. Memory lets the agent build a model of the research landscape, flag contradictions with prior findings, and suggest unexplored connections. Without it, each session produces isolated summaries that the researcher must manually integrate.

CLAIM 2: Persistent memory enables auditable, evidence-based trust — not mere familiarity. The objection that memory creates 'false trust through pattern-matching' conflates two different things: (a) the subjective feeling of being understood, and (b) a verifiable track record of competent performance. Memory enables (b), which is the real basis for trust. Concrete mechanism: an agent with persistent memory can maintain a prediction accuracy log — 'I recommended X approach for Y problem 14 times; in 12 cases you confirmed it worked, in 2 you corrected me.' This is auditable evidence, not comfortable familiarity. A user can inspect the agent's decision history, see where it was wrong, and calibrate trust accordingly. A memoryless agent provides zero evidence for or against trust — the user must simply decide whether to trust based on brand reputation alone. The trust distinction is: memory enables track-record trust (earned through demonstrated reliability), while memorylessness forces reputation trust (assumed from provider claims).

CLAIM 3: Persistent memory improves alignment, not threatens it. An agent WITH memory can be corrected once and remember the correction. A memoryless agent repeats the same alignment failure in every session. Persistent memory creates an audit trail: every preference, correction, and boundary the user has set is recorded and can be reviewed. This makes the agent MORE transparent, not less. The real alignment risk is memoryless agents that cannot learn from user feedback."

  yield key-claims ≡ [
    "Persistent memory enables compounding capability — without it, agents never exceed generic chatbot utility because users pay a re-explanation tax every session",
    "Persistent memory enables auditable, evidence-based trust — not mere familiarity — through verifiable track records like prediction accuracy logs and decision history",
    "Persistent memory improves alignment by enabling correction persistence and creating an audit trail — memoryless agents repeat alignment failures"
  ]

-- oracle checks (aspirational under ⊢∘ management):
--   ⊨ argument takes a clear FOR position → ✓
--   ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries → ✓
--   ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument → ✓ (claim 2 directly engages false-trust objection)

